<methodology slug="hybrid-search">
  <metadata>
    <tier>geek</tier>
    <group>ai</group>
    <domain>ml-engineer</domain>
    <summary>Combine BM25 and vector search with Reciprocal Rank Fusion for 87% precision. Solves mixed semantic+keyword queries better than either retriever alone.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>hybrid-search</tag>
      <tag>rag</tag>
      <tag>vector-search</tag>
      <tag>bm25</tag>
      <tag>fusion</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-25</created>
    <tools>
      <tool>claude-code</tool>
    </tools>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>Hybrid Search: Combining BM25 and Vector Retrieval</title>
    <summary>Hybrid search combines BM25 (sparse/keyword) and vector (dense/semantic) retrieval to maximize precision and recall. Use Reciprocal Rank Fusion (RRF) as the default fusion method — it requires no score normalization and works across different score scales. Add a cross-encoder reranker (Cohere, bge-reranker-v2-m3) only if precision is still insufficient after hybrid. Benchmarks: hybrid + reranking achieves 87% relevant docs in top-10 vs 62% BM25-only and 71% vector-only.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>BM25 excels at exact term matching (product codes, error messages, names); vector search excels at semantic similarity (synonyms, paraphrases, intent). Neither alone handles queries that combine both — enterprise search, technical docs, legal/compliance. Hybrid captures the complementary strengths, with only ~20% latency overhead.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>RAG pipeline serves queries that mix natural language and exact terms (product codes, error messages, legal statute numbers, names)</item>
        <item>Pure vector search precision is inadequate (less than 75% relevant results in top-10) and queries include specific keywords that should match exactly</item>
        <item>Enterprise search over technical documentation where users alternate between concept searches and exact string lookups</item>
        <item>Production system where +15% precision gain justifies ~20% additional latency and complexity</item>
        <item>Replacing an existing BM25-only search with semantic capability without discarding keyword matching</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Corpus is less than 1,000 documents — pure vector search is fast enough and simpler to operate</item>
        <item>All queries are conversational/semantic with no exact term requirements — pure vector search suffices; hybrid adds latency without benefit</item>
        <item>Latency budget is under 20ms — hybrid search (parallel BM25 + vector + fusion) typically costs 40-100ms</item>
        <item>Infrastructure is Elasticsearch-only — native kNN + BM25 in ES is effective without adding a second vector DB</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>
    <section name="fusion-methods">
      <p>Hybrid search requires a fusion strategy to combine BM25 and vector results. Two main approaches exist: Reciprocal Rank Fusion (RRF, rank-based) and linear combination (score-based). RRF is simpler and more robust; linear combination offers fine-grained tuning but requires score normalization.</p>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Use Reciprocal Rank Fusion (RRF) as the default. Formula: RRF_score(d) = SUM(1 / (k + rank_i(d))), k=60. No score normalization needed; works across different score scales.</statement>
        <rationale>RRF ignores actual score magnitudes and only uses rank positions. This makes it robust when BM25 and vector scores are on completely different scales, which is always the case without normalization.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Use linear combination (hybrid_score = alpha * vector + (1-alpha) * bm25) only when RRF is measurably worse on your query set and you have the capacity to normalize and tune. Default alpha=0.7 (semantic-leaning).</statement>
        <rationale>Linear combination provides fine-grained control but requires min-max or z-score normalization of both signals. Without normalization, BM25's unbounded scores dominate entirely.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Apply query-adaptive alpha: quoted phrases → 0.2; product/ref codes → 0.3; short queries → 0.5; natural language → 0.7.</statement>
        <rationale>A fixed alpha is suboptimal for mixed query distributions. A lightweight classifier adds negligible overhead but significantly improves precision across query types.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="Query-adaptive alpha selection">
        <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
def get_alpha(query: str) -> float:
    has_quotes = '"' in query
    has_codes = any(c.isdigit() for c in query)
    is_short = len(query.split()) <= 3
    if has_quotes:
        return 0.2   # Strong keyword preference
    elif has_codes:
        return 0.3   # Keyword preference for product/ref codes
    elif is_short:
        return 0.5   # Balanced for short queries
    else:
        return 0.7   # Semantic preference for natural language
        ]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="reranking">
      <p>Cross-encoder reranking can further improve results by scoring all fusion candidates with a more expensive but accurate model. This is particularly useful when precision is critical and latency permits.</p>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Rerank top-100 candidates (not top-10). Fetch 2-3x the final k for fusion, rerank the pool, then return top-10. A reranker given too few candidates cannot recover good results that ranked poorly in either retriever.</statement>
        <rationale>Reranking adds ~50-100ms and 5x cost compared to retrieval alone. Only worth enabling when precision matters more than latency. Common rerankers: Cohere Rerank (API), bge-reranker-v2-m3 (self-hosted).</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="vector-db-support">
      <p>Different vector databases provide native hybrid search endpoints with varying levels of support. Use native endpoints when available to reduce latency and failure modes.</p>
      <list>
        <item>Weaviate: native hybrid (built-in BM25 + vector, alpha parameter)</item>
        <item>Qdrant: native hybrid (sparse + dense prefetch + FusionQuery RRF)</item>
        <item>Pinecone: native sparse-dense (separate sparse index)</item>
        <item>Elasticsearch: native (kNN + BM25) — good for existing ES infrastructure</item>
        <item>MongoDB Atlas: native hybrid (8.0+; integrated with Atlas Search)</item>
        <item>pgvector: manual (combine with pg_trgm) — PostgreSQL projects only</item>
      </list>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Use native hybrid search endpoints (Weaviate alpha, Qdrant FusionQuery) over manual two-call fusion. Native: lower latency, fewer failure modes, less code.</statement>
        <rationale>Manual fusion requires two separate network calls, two failure modes, and custom RRF implementation. Native endpoints do all of this in a single API call.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="Qdrant native hybrid search">
        <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
from qdrant_client import QdrantClient
from qdrant_client.models import Prefetch, FusionQuery, Fusion

def hybrid_search(client: QdrantClient, query: str, sparse_vector, dense_vector, top_k: int = 10):
    return client.query_points(
        collection_name="docs",
        prefetch=[
            Prefetch(query=sparse_vector, using="sparse", limit=100),
            Prefetch(query=dense_vector, using="dense", limit=100),
        ],
        query=FusionQuery(fusion=Fusion.RRF),
        limit=top_k,
    )
        ]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="bm25-tuning">
      <p>BM25 is a proven keyword matching algorithm, but its performance depends on correct parameter tuning for your corpus.</p>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Set BM25 parameters for your content: short document chunks need b=0.3-0.5; long documents need b=0.75; technical content needs k1=1.5-2.0; general content k1=1.2. Match BM25 tokenizer to corpus language.</statement>
        <rationale>Default BM25 parameters (k1=1.5, b=0.75) are calibrated for long English prose. Applying them to short chunks or code degrades keyword matching significantly.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="monitoring-and-operations">
      <p>Hybrid search adds complexity, so monitoring and data-driven decisions are essential to justify the added cost.</p>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Log retriever attribution: which retriever contributed each successful result. After 2 weeks, if BM25 contributes less than 10% of final results, hybrid may not be justified for that query distribution.</statement>
        <rationale>Hybrid adds complexity and ~20% latency. If your query distribution is purely semantic, the BM25 component is waste. Data-driven decisions about disabling hybrid prevent unnecessary complexity.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Before switching from pure vector to hybrid in production, A/B test on 5% of traffic and measure a quality metric. Latency + complexity cost must be justified by measurable gain.</statement>
        <rationale>Hybrid is not always better. On conversational or creative corpora, BM25 can add noise. Measure on real traffic, not on a benchmark that may not reflect your query distribution.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="failure-modes">
      <p>Understanding common failure modes helps avoid production incidents.</p>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Using raw BM25 scores in linear combination without normalization.</description>
        <reason>BM25 scores for a 10K-document corpus can range 0-30+; vector similarity scores range 0-1. Without min-max or z-score normalization, BM25 dominates entirely and linear combination degrades to pure BM25.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Two parallel network calls for manual fusion without timeout handling.</description>
        <reason>If vector DB is slow but BM25 is fast, waiting for both adds tail latency. Set a timeout on the slower call and fall back to the fast one's results alone.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Using Qdrant hybrid with a standard BM25 library instead of a sparse encoder (SPLADE).</description>
        <reason>Qdrant hybrid requires sparse vectors (e.g., SPLADE) as the sparse component — not the same as a Python BM25 library. Ensure the sparse encoder is deployed and version-pinned.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Fetching top-10 for fusion and then reranking the same 10.</description>
        <reason>The reranker can only reorder what it receives. Fetch top-100 for fusion, rerank the pool, return top-10. A relevant document at rank 15 is invisible to a reranker that receives only 10 candidates.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Score normalization for linear fusion is non-trivial: BM25 scores are unbounded; vector scores are 0-1; without proper min-max or z-score normalization, one signal dominates.</description>
        <reason>Proper score normalization requires understanding the distribution of both signals across your corpus. It is dataset-specific and requires empirical tuning.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Alpha tuning is dataset-specific: the optimal alpha value for one corpus may perform poorly on another.</description>
        <reason>Without empirical tuning on your specific query distribution and corpus, a fixed alpha may not be optimal. Consider implementing query-adaptive alpha selection.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>RRF ignores actual score magnitudes: two documents with very different relevance scores but similar ranks get similar RRF scores.</description>
        <reason>This may not reflect true quality difference. If magnitude matters, switch to linear combination with proper normalization.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Reranking top-100 adds 50-100ms and 5x cost compared to retrieval alone.</description>
        <reason>Only enable reranking when precision matters more than speed.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>BM25 tokenization matters: if BM25 uses a standard English tokenizer but the corpus contains code, product codes, or non-English text, keyword matching degrades significantly.</description>
        <reason>Always configure BM25's tokenizer to match your corpus characteristics.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Hybrid search from separate stores (manual RRF) has higher failure surface than native hybrid (Weaviate/Qdrant built-in).</description>
        <reason>Two network calls = two failure modes. Native hybrid avoids this.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <section name="best-practices">
      <list>
        <item>Start with RRF as the default fusion method — it requires no score normalization, works across different score scales, and performs well out of the box; only switch to linear combination if RRF is measurably worse on your query set</item>
        <item>Use native hybrid search endpoints (Weaviate alpha, Qdrant FusionQuery) over manual two-call fusion — lower latency, fewer failure modes, less code</item>
        <item>Rerank top-100, not top-10 — the reranker is only as good as the candidates it receives; fetching top-10 for fusion and then reranking gives the reranker too little to work with</item>
        <item>Monitor retriever attribution: log which retriever contributed to each successful result — after 2 weeks, if BM25 contributes less than 10% of final results, hybrid may not be needed for that query distribution</item>
        <item>Apply query-adaptive alpha: queries with quoted phrases or codes should use alpha=0.2-0.3; natural language questions should use alpha=0.7; implement a lightweight classifier to select dynamically</item>
        <item>Set BM25 parameters for your content: short document chunks need b=0.3-0.5; long documents need b=0.75; technical content needs higher k1=1.5-2.0</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="agentic-workflow">
      <p>A search agent receives a query, classifies it by type (semantic, keyword, mixed), and selects the appropriate fusion strategy.</p>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>For mixed queries, the agent runs BM25 and vector search in parallel, applies RRF fusion, and optionally passes the top-100 candidates through a cross-encoder reranker to get the final top-10.</statement>
        <rationale>This approach maximizes recall and precision while keeping latency bounded.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>The agent logs which retriever contributed to each final result for monitoring and tuning.</statement>
        <rationale>This data drives decisions about whether hybrid search is still necessary and whether the cost is justified.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Query classifier subagent — detects if query contains exact terms (codes, quoted phrases, names) and returns {type: "semantic"|"keyword"|"hybrid", alpha: float}</item>
        <item>Hybrid retrieval tool — wraps the vector DB's native hybrid search or implements RRF fusion; returns ranked {doc_id, score, retriever_source} list</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <templates>
      <template path="templates/rrf.py" purpose="Reciprocal Rank Fusion implementation (less than 40 lines, merge BM25 and vector results)"/>
      <template path="templates/qdrant-hybrid.py" purpose="Qdrant native hybrid search with FusionQuery"/>
    </templates>
